              <tr><td><strong>Database calendar</strong></td><td>Multi-channel content ops</td><td>Notion, Airtable</td><td>2-4 hours</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Specialised platform</strong></td><td>Agencies, enterprise teams</td><td>CoSchedule, Sprout Social</td><td>1-2 days</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Social scheduler</strong></td><td>Social-first brands</td><td>Buffer, Later, Hootsuite</td><td>&lt; 1 hour</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Editorial calendar</strong></td><td>Long-form publishers</td><td>WordPress editorial calendar</td><td>Native to CMS</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content calendar examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Local business — physical therapy clinic</h3>
        <p>A PT clinic publishes 8 blog posts per month addressing patient-search queries, 3 GBP posts per week, and 2 emails per month. Their calendar is a single Google Sheet with columns for date, channel, topic, keyword, and owner. Result over five months: organic traffic tripled, bookings up 40%.</p>
        <h3>2. Ecommerce brand — automated publishing</h3>
        <p>A DTC brand runs 30 SEO articles per month through theStacc, all planned and briefed 45 days out. The calendar auto-syncs into Shopify. Organic sessions grew from 12k to 84k over six months.</p>
        <h3>3. B2B SaaS — quarterly campaigns</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS team plans in 90-day sprints. Each quarter has a theme (integrations, use cases, industry-vertical). Blogs, emails, webinars, and LinkedIn posts all ladder to the theme. The calendar drives 60% higher engagement per campaign vs pre-calendar era.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content calendar vs editorial calendar</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content calendar</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Tactical publishing schedule</li>
              <li>Row per publication, per channel</li>
              <li>Owner + date + status + assets</li>
              <li>Weekly + monthly cadence review</li>
              <li>Used by writers, designers, publishers</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Editorial calendar</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Strategic theme calendar</li>
              <li>Campaigns, arcs, narrative flow</li>
              <li>Quarter + month view</li>
              <li>Quarterly strategy alignment</li>
              <li>Used by strategy and leadership</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>The editorial calendar tells you what stories to tell this quarter. The content calendar tells you which specific piece publishes on Tuesday.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 content calendar best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Plan 2-4 weeks ahead, always.</strong> Anything under a week means you are firefighting. Anything over 4 weeks locks you out of timely content.</li>
          <li><strong>Reserve 20-30% flex slots.</strong> Trending moments, product news, and reactive posts need room in the calendar.</li>
          <li><strong>Balance funnel stages.</strong> Track top / middle / bottom of funnel distribution. Aim for roughly 60/25/15 or your team's ratio.</li>
          <li><strong>One source of truth.</strong> One calendar for all channels beats separate calendars per team. Cross-channel repurposing becomes obvious.</li>
          <li><strong>Weekly review, monthly rebalance.</strong> Weekly for status hygiene, monthly for topic mix and cadence adjustments.</li>
          <li><strong>Link every row to its brief.</strong> The calendar tells you what publishes when; the brief tells the writer what to make. Both should be one click apart.</li>
          <li><strong>Track outcomes on the calendar.</strong> Ranking, sessions, conversions per row. Retrospective becomes instant.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — overplanning</div>
          <p>A perfectly filled calendar that never survives contact with reality is worse than a lean one. Plan 70-80% of slots, keep the rest flex. Rigidity beats brittle plans every time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content calendar mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building a calendar without a strategy.</strong> The calendar sequences your strategy; it does not replace it.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting unrealistic cadences.</strong> "3 blogs a week forever" collapses in month two. Match cadence to capacity.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring channel differences.</strong> LinkedIn and Instagram do not want the same cadence or format.</li>
          <li><strong>No flex slots.</strong> Full calendars make timely content impossible.</li>
          <li><strong>Never reviewing outcomes.</strong> Publishing without measuring is broadcasting, not marketing.</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple disconnected calendars.</strong> Social team, blog team, and email team on different tools = duplicated work.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How far ahead should you plan a content calendar?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Plan 2-4 weeks ahead as a working default. Keep 20-30% flexibility open for reactive posts and trending topics. Some evergreen pieces can be scheduled 2-3 months out; timely posts get slotted in the week they run.</p></div></div>
          </div>
